[1] Belize
Date: Fri, 22 Jul 2005 13:28:49 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Reporter Belize, Belize, 22 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://www.reporter.bz/index.php?option=content&task=view&id=509&Itemid=2>

Belize fights dengue fever - all 118 cases
--------------------------------------------------------
118 cases of dengue fever have been detected in the capital city, Belmopan
and 10 surrounding villages in the Cayo district: Armenia, Camalote, Cotton
Tree, Las Flores, Ontario, Roaring Creek, Salvapan, San Martin, Unitedville
and Valley of Peace, said a Government Information Service release.
The ministry is now asking the public's help in containing the outbreak by
a cleanup campaign to destroy mosquito breeding sites.
"We call on the public to assist with what we are doing in the Ministry of
Health -- to control the situation by eliminating all potential breeding
sites," said Director of Health Services Dr. Errol Vanzie. "If we control
the breeding sites of mosquitoes, we can avoid dengue."
The public is asked to clean up and remove all containers that collect
water that might serve as a breeding site for mosquitoes. This means burn,
bury or dispose of containers, like old tires and bottles, that can collect
water. Water vats, drums, buckets and all other containers used to collect
water should be covered.
Drums should be washed out at least once a week. The public is also asked
to use insecticide and/or larvicide provided by the health ministry to kill
off the mosquitoes for areas such as ponds or other low-lying areas covered
by water.
Vanzie told Channel 7 News, that destroying all breeding sites does not
mean an end to the outbreak, "there are cases incubating that have not
shown symptoms yet. And even after we've eliminated the mosquitoes, at
least for a week we will still continue to have new cases."
The presence of dengue was confirmed by laboratory analysis in Belize, and
another batch of samples has been sent to laboratories abroad for further
confirmation.
Residents of the above-mentioned villages and neighbouring communities are
asked to report any sudden onset of fever, headache, muscle and joint pain,
rash and pain behind the eyes to their community Nurses Aides, voluntary
collaborators or community leaders who will then report to the hospital
authorities.
Vanzie said anyone who shows any of these signs doesn't need to go to the
clinic. They should drink lots of liquids and rest. Patients with the fever
should be nursed in screened rooms. Tylenol may be taken for the pain,
however, victims should not take any medication that contains aspirin,
because it makes it worse.
He also indicated that cases had also been reported in 6 villages in the
Corozal district as well as Belize City, increasing the chance for the
disease to spread throughout the country and result in a major outbreak.
Classical dengue displays flu-like symptoms. It is self-limiting in the
sense that it comes and goes through its course and within 3 to 4 days it
disappears by itself.
The symptoms are usually pain, generalised pain, especially in the joints,
muscle ache, pain behind the eye (which is very specific to dengue), and a
high percentage of cases will manifest rash.
Vanzie adds that Belize has never had a case of dengue hemorrhagic fever
and, in fact, very few cases have the potential to develop into hemorrhagic
fever.
The Ministry of Health will also be intensifying its spraying operations.
Vector control personnel will also be out applying larvicide to destroy larvae.
Belize is a small country with 250 000 residents.
[Byline: William Ysguirre]
