[4] India (Ahmedabad)
Date: Thu, 21 Jul 2005 18:28:25 -0400 (EDT)
From: ProMED <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ahmedabad Newsline, 21 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://cities.expressindia.com/fullstory.php?newsid=140311>

8 cases of suspected dengue have been reported in Rajkot
--------------------------------------------------
To beat the dengue bug, RMC has a brainwave: cover up
RMC [the Rajkot Municipal Corporation] asks housing societies to pitch in.
In a precautionary measure against dengue, RMC has asked school authorities
to instruct students to wear dresses covering their hands and legs, even as
8 schools were given notice to remove water logging and leaking after
_Aedes aegypti_ larvae was found in their water reservoirs.
A total of 8 cases of suspected dengue have been reported in Rajkot so far.
Larvae were also found at 16 places in Rajkot on Thursday.
According to RMC Commissioner Mukesh Kumar, all schools have been asked to
see that students wear dresses that cover their hands and legs. School
authorities have also been asked [relax dress codes]. Besides, Mukesh Kumar
also contacted the presidents of various housing societies, architects and
builders to join hands in anti-dengue drive.
The RMC health department has said that more _Aedes aegypti_ breeding sites
were found at in the old as well as new city areas.
According to the health department, it has also started a door-to-door
campaign to take blood tests of those suffering from fever.
Meanwhile, Gujarat High Court on Wednesday took suo motu cognisance of the
rising number of dengue cases in Ahmedabad and ordered the formation of 3
committees, under the registrar-general of the high court, to inspect
affected areas under the jurisdiction of Ahmedabad Municipal Corporation
(AMC) and Ahmedabad Urban Development Authority (AUDA).
A division bench of K R Vyas and A K Mehta has directed the committees to
visit areas and find whether local authorities have adhered to provisions
of municipal law pertaining to public health. The committees have also been
asked to photograph or videograph and draw panchnamas [file reports or
affidavits] of affected areas and people to uncover the causes behind the
outbreak.
The committees have also been asked to look into instances of negligence in
cleaning garbage and waterlogging and report to the high court.
